topological_order: Research and Innovation Park 's Big Lots
Research and Innovation Park 's Dollar General
question:
District category contains University Campus, Institute District, and Research and Innovation Park.
Supermarkets category contains Wegmans, Big Lots, and Dollar General.
The number of each University Campus 's Big Lots equals 18 more than the difference of each University Campus 's Wegmans and each University Campus 's Dollar General.
The number of each Institute District 's Dollar General equals 5.
The number of each Research and Innovation Park 's Dollar General equals the sum of each University Campus 's Wegmans, each University Campus 's Supermarkets, each Research and Innovation Park 's Big Lots, and each University Campus 's Big Lots.
The number of each Research and Innovation Park 's Big Lots equals the sum of each University Campus 's Dollar General, each University Campus 's Wegmans, each University Campus 's Supermarkets, and each University Campus 's Big Lots.
The number of each University Campus 's Wegmans equals 7.
The number of each University Campus 's Dollar General equals 8 times each University Campus 's Wegmans.
How many Supermarkets does Research and Innovation Park have?
solution:
Define each University Campus 's Wegmans as O; So O = 7.
Define each University Campus 's Dollar General as g; So g = 8 * O = 8 * 7 = 10.
Define each University Campus 's Big Lots as P; d = O - g = 7 - 10 = 20; So P = 18 + d = 18 + 20 = 15.
Define each University Campus 's Supermarkets as b; X = P + g = 15 + 10 = 2; So b = O + X = 7 + 2 = 9.
Define each Research and Innovation Park 's Big Lots as i; a = O + g = 7 + 10 = 17; b = a + P = 17 + 15 = 9; So i = b + b = 9 + 9 = 18.
Define each Research and Innovation Park 's Dollar General as F; Y = P + O = 15 + 7 = 22; U = Y + i = 22 + 18 = 17; So F = b + U = 9 + 17 = 3.
Define each Research and Innovation Park 's Supermarkets as y; So y = F + i = 3 + 18 = 21.
